In [30]:
wcss = []

for i in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(
        n_clusters=i,
        init='k-means++',
        random_state=42
    )
    kmeans.fit(car_df)
    # kmeans.inertial_ returns the calculated WCSS Values
    wcss.append([i, kmeans.inertia_])

wcss_dataframe = pd.DataFrame(wcss, columns=["clusters", "wcss value"])

C. On the above visual, highlight which are the possible Elbow points.¶

In [32]:
"""
From Elbow Method it is Clear that we have 4 Clusters
So elbow point is 4
the number of clusters increases, the WCSS value will start to decrease. WCSS value is largest when K = 1. When we analyze the graph we can see that the graph will rapidly change at a point and thus creating an elbow shape. From this point, the graph starts to move almost parallel to the X-axis. The K value corresponding to this point is the optimal K value or an optimal number of clusters.
"""
Out[32]:

When we analyze the graph we can see that the graph will rapidly change at a point and thus creating an elbow shape. From this point, the graph starts to move almost parallel to the X-axis. The K value corresponding to this point is the optimal K value or an optimal number of clusters.\n'

G. Pass a new DataPoint and predict which cluster it belongs to¶

In [42]:
from scipy.spatial.distance import cdist
clusters = range(1, 10)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(car_df)
    prediction = model.predict(car_df)
    meanDistortions.append(sum(np.min(
        cdist(car_df, model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / car_df.shape[0])


plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Average distortion')

def plotPieChart(df):

    i = 1
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=1, figsize=(10, 5))
    plt.figure(i)
    df.groupby(df['class']).size().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%.2f')
    axs.set_ylabel('class', size=22)
    axs.yaxis.label.set_color('red')
    axs.xaxis.label.set_color('green')
    axs.spines['bottom'].set_color('red')
    axs.spines['top'].set_color('red')
    plt.show()

var_exp = [(i / tot) * 100 for i in sorted(e_vals, reverse=True)]
cum_var_exp = np.cumsum(var_exp)
print("Cumulative Variance Explained", cum_var_exp)

Variables included are metric level or nominal level.
Features are low dimensional in nature.

Bartlett-Test: The Bartlett test is statistically significant as.

H1: Variables are correlated.
"""

B. Explain advantages and limitations of PCA¶

In [81]:
"""
The main advantage of PCA is dimensionality (features) reduction. It improves algorithm performance by removing correlated features but there is some information loss
Removes Correlated Features: ...
Improves Algorithm Performance: ...
Reduces Overfitting: ...
Improves Visualization: ...
Independent variables become less interpretable: ...
Data standardization is must before PCA: ...
Information Loss

Limitations of PCA are that it may miss nonlinear data patterns (a); structure that is not orthogonal to previous PCs may not be well characterized (b); and PC1 (blue) may not split two obvious clusters (c). PC2 is shown in orange.
"""
